# Workflow plan

Use this reference only in Stage 2, after the support team approves the Stage 1 direction. Stage 2 may discover, construct, and statically or mock validate a potential workflow. Actual paid or externally consequential execution has a separate gate.

## Discovery

Translate the approved system into required roles and capabilities. Resolve current candidate endpoint IDs, then inspect command-specific input and output schemas and raw pricing when cost affects the design. Record verified observations, their source and date, and unresolved facts. Replace deprecated, missing, schema-incompatible, or unverified candidates instead of guessing.

The verified endpoint matrix should include role, endpoint, required inputs, emitted outputs, relevant constraints, raw billing unit, fallback condition, and verification status.

## Construction

Choose the deliverable explicitly: a reusable fixed workflow graph or an execution plan for conditional orchestration. Give every node one role. Define typed inputs, deterministic preprocessing, model nodes, QA nodes, retry and fallback branches, failure handling, and output manifest. For each connection, prove that the upstream output matches the downstream input.

A node contract contains node ID, responsibility, inputs and provenance, endpoint or deterministic operation, verified fields, outputs, blocking failures, retry policy, fallback, and observability fields. Keep candidate counts and retry limits explicit.

## Static and mock validation

Before paid execution:

- validate artifact syntax and supported node types;
- require node IDs and references to resolve;
- require dependencies for every referenced node;
- verify endpoint IDs and fields against the recorded schema;
- ensure model-to-model data shapes connect correctly;
- confirm outputs include every requested deliverable and relevant metadata;
- run fixture inputs and synthetic outputs through success, rejection, retry, fallback, and terminal-failure paths;
- confirm QA failures cannot silently reach delivery;
- calculate a cost envelope from raw units, candidate caps, and retry caps without inventing unknown mappings.

Static and mock validation proves graph behavior and contracts, not creative output quality. Label the results accordingly.

## Execution gate

Return the potential workflow, verified endpoint matrix, validation results, cost envelope, open risks, and a bounded sample proposal. Then request separate explicit execution approval. Do not call paid endpoints, use customer assets in generation, or imply a sample was run before approval.

After approval, run the smallest representative sample, preserve endpoint IDs, parameters, request IDs, outputs, failures, and observed costs, and score against predeclared blocking criteria. Revise from observed failures. Report what passed, failed, changed, and remains unproven. Never infer production reliability from one sample.
